(Haiti) Maersk has approved shipments of 23 containers filled with shelter tool kits, plastic buckets, vehicles, rice, family kits and other relief items on behalf of the International Federation of Red Cross (IFRC) and the WFP. This offer is extended to the whole humanitarian community involved in the Haiti response, and the Maersk Group, which allocated USD 125,000 in international shipping support, is receiving further requests from various NGOs. Additionally, Maersk has donated a refrigerated container for medical supply storage in Haiti, while Damco has provided forklifts, operators and other services for local operations to run more efficiently. (Haiti): Cayman Water Company has donated US$3,375 to buy 75 water filtration units to help combat cholera and other pathogens at risk of contaminating Haiti?s drinking water in the wake of Hurricane Matthew. The money will go toward the purchase of Sawyer PointON water purifier units and five-gallon buckets manufactured in Haiti by Plastech Industries. Donations will be managed by the Pan American Development Fund, according to organizers.The response is part of the Haiti Relief Effort project by the Caribbean Desalination Association?s newly established Humanitarian Committee through Pan American Development Fund, Caribbean Desalination Association?s Humanitarian Committee(from Cayman Water Company)

(Haiti): MSR, which produces outdoor water filtration and purification solutions, said it donated more than 100,000 of its Aquatabs purification tablets to the Haitian Health Foundation to help with the continuing aftermath of Hurricane Matthew. The donation adds to the 100 MSR Community Chlorine Makers that have already been distributed throughout Haiti in partnership with Operation Blessing International, in hopes of supplying more communities with safe drinking water.(from Mountain Safety Research)

The project aims at facilitating the return of children to school in areas affected by Hurricane Matthew by rehabilitating and providing equipment to children, teachers and for food at school programs, while conducting disaster risk reduction at school and community level to increase the resilience of targeted areas. The project will rehabilitate 60 schools for a total amount of beneficiaries of 21000 in three departements : Nippes (26 schools), South (8 schools) and Grande Anse (26 schools).  (Nov 2016-May 2018 portion of multiyear award, 2016-2019 total EUR 1.7 million)
